{"title_page": "Jenny Mikakos", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix= [[The Honourable]]\n| name            = Jenny Mikakos\n| nationality     = Australian\n| honorific-suffix= [[Victorian Legislative Council|MLC]]\n| image           = Cabinet 2018-160L.jpg\n| image_upright   = 1.15\n| caption = Mikakos (left), with Governor of Victoria Linda Dessau\n| office          = Member of the [[Victorian Legislative Council]] for [[Northern Metropolitan Region]]\n| term_start      = 18 September 1999\n| portfolio       = Minister for Health, \nMinister for Ambulance Services, Minister for the Coordination of Health and Human Services - COVID-19\n| predecessor     =\n| successor       =\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1969|1|25}}\n| birth_place     =\n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| party           = [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]]\n| spouse          =\n| profession      =\n| signature       =\n| footnotes       =\n|}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2014}}\n'''Jenny Mikakos''' (born 25 January 1969) is an Australian politician for the [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]]. She is currently the Minister for Health and the Minister for Ambulance Services and a [[Members of the Victorian Legislative Council, 2006-2010|Member of the Legislative Council]] for [[Northern Metropolitan Region]].<ref name=\"Mikakos\">{{cite encyclopedia| editor = Suzannah Pearce| encyclopedia = Who's Who in Australia Live!| title = MIKAKOS Jenny| date = 2006-11-17| publisher = Crown Content Pty Ltd| location = North Melbourne, Vic}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\nMikakos was first elected as the Member for Jika Jika Province in the State of [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]] in September 1999.{{ref|JikaJika}} From 1999 until 2006, she represented the [[Legislative Council]] province of [[Jika Jika, Victoria|Jika Jika]].<ref name=\"Mikakos\"/> Mikakos' electorate was abolished at the [[2006 Victorian state election|2006 election]] as part of major reforms of the Legislative Council introduced after the 2002 election, but she won the second position on the Labor ticket for the replacement electorate, the larger, five-member Northern Metropolitan Region. She was first on the Labor ticket at the 2010, 2014 and 2018 election. {{cn}}\n\nFrom 2002 until 2007, she was appointed Parliamentary Secretary for Justice. From 2007 until 2010 she was appointed Parliamentary Secretary for Planning. {{cn}}\n\nFrom 2010 until 2014 she was the Shadow Minister for Community Services, Children, Youth Affairs, Youth Justice and Seniors and Ageing. {{cn}}\n\nFrom 2014 until 2018, she was appointed Minister for Families and Children, Early Childhood Education and Youth Affairs in the Andrews Labor Government. {{cn}}\n\nIn November 2018, Mikakos was appointed the Minister for Health and Minister for Ambulance Services following the re-election of the Andrews Labor Government. {{cn}}\n\nIn March 2020, she was appointed Deputy Leader of the Government in the Legislative Council. {{cn}}\n\nIn April 2020, Mikakos was appointed as the Minister for the Coordination of Health and Human Services COVID-19 as part of the Victorian Government's response to the coronavirus global pandemic.  This appointment followed media coverage of comments which Mikakos made regarding a GP who tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Woodley|first=Matt|url=https://www1.racgp.org.au/newsgp/professional/doctors-rally-around-coronavirus-gp-after-criticis|title=Doctors rally around coronavirus GP after criticism from minister|date=9 March 2020|work=newsGP|access-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn Parliament, Mikakos voted against the human cloning  bill but for stem cell research, for abortion decriminalisation, for assisted reproductive technology reforms and for dying with dignity laws. These bills were subject to a conscience votes in the Labor Party. {{cn}}\n\n==Personal life==\n\nJenny Mikakos was the first woman of Greek descent elected to an Australian Parliament. She grew up in Northcote, in her electorate, to a migrant working-class family.\n\nShe attended [[Ivanhoe Girls' Grammar School]], Thornbury High School,<ref name=\"Mikakos\"/> and the [[University of Melbourne]] where she obtained arts and law degrees. Before her election to Parliament, Mikakos worked as a commercial and tax lawyer for [[King & Wood Mallesons]] and  Jerrard & Stuk. She was briefly a Councillor with the City of Northcote in the early 1990s.{{ref|career}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n#{{note|left}} Austin, P., [http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/alp-heavies-tackle-faction-fracas-before-poll/2006/02/26/1140888749262.html ALP heavies tackle faction fracas before poll], ''The Age'', 27 February 2006\n#{{note|SocialistLeft}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20060427003109/http://www.crikey.com.au/articles/2002/06/16-deliajune19.html With Crikey's Delia Delegate, all the ALP dirty laundry is on the table], 16 June 2002\n#{{note|hard-left}} Carney, S., [http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/06/17/1023864403072.html Labor supremos back new alliance], ''The Age'', 18 June 2002\n#{{note|career}} [http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/handbook/preview_main.cfm?menuid=3&listtype=report&listid=12 Parliamentary handbook]\n#{{note|JikaJika}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20060302060455/http://home.vicnet.net.au/~jmikakos/ Jenny Mikakos MP Member for Jika Jika Province]\n#{{note|AJF}} [http://www.gamblingresearch.org.au/__ca2569020010922a.nsf/Print/d2414d006c362bfdca256e9b00092112?OpenDocument&Click= Jenny Mikakos, Chair of the Aboriginal Justice Forum]{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n#{{note|GLBT}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20060302060455/http://home.vicnet.net.au/~jmikakos/ Jenny Mikakos MP Member for Jika Jika Province]\n#{{note|WCSAC}} [http://www.justice.vic.gov.au/CA256902000FE154/Lookup/DOJ_CORRECTIONS_PART3/$file/Better_Pathways_Strategy.pdf Women\u2019s Correctional Services Advisory Committee]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060629145052/http://147.202.41.181/discover/news/documents/ALSONewsJan06.pdf Celebrating 25 years of the Alternative Life Styles Organisation (ALSO)]\n* [http://www.evolutionpublishing.com.au/mcv/index2.php?option=com_content&do_pdf=1&id=105 Homophobia rife in Vic Libs]{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* Munro, I., [http://www.theage.com.au/news/National/Jail-birds/2005/03/30/1111862459645.html?from=moreStories Jail Birds], ''The Age'', 31 March 2005\n* [http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/labor-claims-school-bias/2006/02/27/1141020024526.html Labor claims school bias], ''The Age'', 28 February 2006\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060302060455/http://home.vicnet.net.au/~jmikakos/ Jenny Mikakos MP Member for Jika Jika Province Parliamentary Secretary for Justice]\n* Boyle, P., [https://web.archive.org/web/20060225194852/http://www.dsp.org.au/dsp/ta/ta8n2pb.htm The Australian Political Situation and the Coming Federal Election],\n* Hannan, E., [http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/06/07/1022982768333.html Pre-election Labor split looming], ''The Age'', 8 June 2002\n\n==Further reading==\n* Healy, Ernest (1995), 'Ethnic ALP Branches - The Balkanisation of Labor Revisited,' in ''People and Place'', Vol.3, No.3, Pages 48\u201353.\n* Lovell, D.W.; McAllister, I.; Maley, W.; Kukathas, C.; (1998), ''The Australian Political System,'' Longman, South Melbourne. {{ISBN|0-582-81027-2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://vicvote.review/council/members/Jenny%20Mikakos.html Parliamentary voting record of Jenny Mikakos at Victorian Parliament Tracker]\n\n{{Cabinet of Victoria}}\n{{VicCurrentMLCs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mikakos, Jenny}}\n[[Category:Australian Labor Party members of the Parliament of Victoria]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Council]]\n[[Category:Australian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Victorian Legislative Council]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix= [[The Honourable]]\n| name            = Jenny Mikakos\n| nationality     = Australian\n| honorific-suffix= [[Victorian Legislative Council|MLC]]\n| image           = Cabinet 2018-160L.jpg\n| image_upright   = 1.15\n| caption = Mikakos (left), with Governor of Victoria Linda Dessau\n| office          = Member of the [[Victorian Legislative Council]] for [[Northern Metropolitan Region]]\n| term_start      = 18 September 1999\n| portfolio       = Minister for Health, \nMinister for Ambulance Services, Minister for the Coordination of Health and Human Services - COVID-19\n| predecessor     =\n| successor       =\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1969|1|25}}\n| birth_place     =\n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| party           = [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]]\n| spouse          =\n| profession      =\n| signature       =\n| footnotes       =\n|}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2014}}\n'''Jenny Mikakos''' (born 25 January 1969) is an Australian politician for the [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]]. She is currently the Minister for Health and the Minister for Ambulance Services and a [[Members of the Victorian Legislative Council, 2006-2010|Member of the Legislative Council]] for [[Northern Metropolitan Region]].<ref name=\"Mikakos\">{{cite encyclopedia| editor = Suzannah Pearce| encyclopedia = Who's Who in Australia Live!| title = MIKAKOS Jenny| date = 2006-11-17| publisher = Crown Content Pty Ltd| location = North Melbourne, Vic}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\nMikakos was first elected as the Member for Jika Jika Province in the State of [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]] in September 1999.{{ref|JikaJika}} From 1999 until 2006, she represented the [[Legislative Council]] province of [[Jika Jika, Victoria|Jika Jika]].<ref name=\"Mikakos\"/> Mikakos' electorate was abolished at the [[2006 Victorian state election|2006 election]] as part of major reforms of the Legislative Council introduced after the 2002 election, but she won the second position on the Labor ticket for the replacement electorate, the larger, five-member Northern Metropolitan Region. She was first on the Labor ticket at the 2010, 2014 and 2018 election.\n\nFrom 2002 until 2007, she was appointed Parliamentary Secretary for Justice. From 2007 until 2010 she was appointed Parliamentary Secretary for Planning.\n\nFrom 2010 until 2014 she was the Shadow Minister for Community Services, Children, Youth Affairs, Youth Justice and Seniors and Ageing.\n\nFrom 2014 until 2018, she was appointed Minister for Families and Children, Early Childhood Education and Youth Affairs in the Andrews Labor Government.\n\nIn November 2018, Mikakos was appointed the Minister for Health and Minister for Ambulance Services following the re-election of the Andrews Labor Government.\n\nIn March 2020, she was appointed Deputy Leader of the Government in the Legislative Council.\n\nIn April 2020, Mikakos was appointed as the Minister for the Coordination of Health and Human Services COVID-19 as part of the Victorian Government's response to the coronavirus global pandemic.  This appointment followed media coverage of comments which Mikakos made regarding a GP who tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Woodley|first=Matt|url=https://www1.racgp.org.au/newsgp/professional/doctors-rally-around-coronavirus-gp-after-criticis|title=Doctors rally around coronavirus GP after criticism from minister|date=9 March 2020|work=newsGP|access-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn Parliament, Mikakos voted against the human cloning  bill but for stem cell research, for abortion decriminalisation, for assisted reproductive technology reforms and for dying with dignity laws. These bills were subject to a conscience votes in the Labor Party.\n\n==Personal life==\n\nJenny Mikakos was the first woman of Greek descent elected to an Australian Parliament. She grew up in Northcote, in her electorate, to a migrant working-class family.\n\nShe attended [[Ivanhoe Girls' Grammar School]], Thornbury High School,<ref name=\"Mikakos\"/> and the [[University of Melbourne]] where she obtained arts and law degrees. Before her election to Parliament, Mikakos worked as a commercial and tax lawyer for [[King & Wood Mallesons]] and  Jerrard & Stuk. She was briefly a Councillor with the City of Northcote in the early 1990s.{{ref|career}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n#{{note|left}} Austin, P., [http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/alp-heavies-tackle-faction-fracas-before-poll/2006/02/26/1140888749262.html ALP heavies tackle faction fracas before poll], ''The Age'', 27 February 2006\n#{{note|SocialistLeft}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20060427003109/http://www.crikey.com.au/articles/2002/06/16-deliajune19.html With Crikey's Delia Delegate, all the ALP dirty laundry is on the table], 16 June 2002\n#{{note|hard-left}} Carney, S., [http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/06/17/1023864403072.html Labor supremos back new alliance], ''The Age'', 18 June 2002\n#{{note|career}} [http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/handbook/preview_main.cfm?menuid=3&listtype=report&listid=12 Parliamentary handbook]\n#{{note|JikaJika}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20060302060455/http://home.vicnet.net.au/~jmikakos/ Jenny Mikakos MP Member for Jika Jika Province]\n#{{note|AJF}} [http://www.gamblingresearch.org.au/__ca2569020010922a.nsf/Print/d2414d006c362bfdca256e9b00092112?OpenDocument&Click= Jenny Mikakos, Chair of the Aboriginal Justice Forum]{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }