{"title_page": "St. Paul's Episcopal Church (Brooklyn)", "text_new": "__NOTOC__{{Infobox NRHP \n| name =St. Paul's Episcopal Church Carroll Street\n| nrhp_type =\n| image = St. Paul's Episcopal Church of Brooklyn.jpg\n| image_size = 325px\n| caption = (2013)\n| location= 199 Carroll Street<br />[[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|40|55|N|73|58|25|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = New York City#New York#USA\n| built =1867-1884<ref name=aia>{{cite aia5|page=626}}</ref>\n| architect= [[Richard Upjohn & Son]; Richard M. Upjohn]<br />[[Ralph Adams Cram]]\n| architecture= [[Gothic revival architecture|High Victorian Gothic]]<ref name=aia />\n| added = December 21, 1989\n| governing_body = Vestry\n| refnum=89002086<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''St. Paul's Episcopal Church of Brooklyn''' at 199 Carroll Street in the [[Carroll Gardens, Brooklyn|Carroll Gardens]] neighborhood of [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]] was built from 1867 to 1884 and was designed by [[Richard Upjohn & Son]]<ref name=aia /> in the [[Gothic revival architecture|High Victorian Gothic style]].  It was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1989.<ref name=nris/>\n\nThe parish is part of the [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America]] in the [[Episcopal Diocese of Long Island]], part of the worldwide [[Anglican Communion]], in the [[Anglo-Catholic]] tradition.\n\n== Parish history ==\nSt. Paul's was founded on Christmas Day of 1849, in [[South Brooklyn]], then the quickly developing southward expansion of old [[Brooklyn Heights]]. New homes and businesses were covering old countryside, farmland, and shoreline; [[industrialization]] was bringing a new way of life to the [[City of Brooklyn]], waves of immigrants from the nations of the world were arriving and the [[American Civil War]] was looming.  This was also the era when the [[Anglican Communion]] of Churches was experiencing a renewed vision of their catholic faith and order often called the \"Anglo-Catholic Revival\" of the [[Oxford Movement]]. Saint Paul's was formed in heady days of philosophical, social, economic, and religious change.<ref name=\"nrhpinv_ny\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3330|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration:St. Paul's Protestant Episcopal Church|date=October 1989|accessdate=2011-02-20 |author=Kathleen LaFrank|publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]}} ''See also:'' {{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3331|title=Accompanying six photos}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*{{Portal-inline|Christianity}}\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline|St. Paul's Episcopal Church (Brooklyn, New York)}}\n*[http://www.stpaulscarrollst.org/ Official website]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Pauls Church, Brooklyn}}\n[[Category:Properties of religious function on the National Register of Historic Places in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival church buildings in New York City]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1866]]\n[[Category:19th-century Episcopal church buildings]]\n[[Category:Churches in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Catholic church buildings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Episcopal church buildings in New York City]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Culture of Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Richard Michell Upjohn church buildings]]\n[[Category:Richard Upjohn church buildings]]\n[[Category:Carroll Gardens, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:1866 establishments in New York (state)]]\n\n\n{{Brooklyn-NRHP-stub}}\n{{Brooklyn-church-stub}}\n", "text_old": "__NOTOC__{{Infobox NRHP \n| name =St. Paul's Episcopal Church\n| nrhp_type =\n| image = St. Paul's Episcopal Church of Brooklyn.jpg\n| image_size = 325px\n| caption = (2013)\n| location= 423 Clinton Street<br />[[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|40|55|N|73|58|25|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = New York City#New York#USA\n| built =1867-1884<ref name=aia>{{cite aia5|page=626}}</ref>\n| architect= [[Richard Upjohn & Son]]<br />[[Ralph Adams Cram]]\n| architecture= [[Gothic revival architecture|High Victorian Gothic]]<ref name=aia />\n| added = December 21, 1989\n| governing_body = Private\n| refnum=89002086<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''St. Paul's Episcopal Church of Brooklyn''' at 423 Clinton Street at Carroll Street in the [[Carroll Gardens, Brooklyn|Carroll Gardens]] neighborhood of [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]] was built from 1867 to 1884 and was designed by [[Richard Upjohn & Son]]<ref name=aia /> in the [[Gothic revival architecture|High Victorian Gothic style]].  It was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1989.<ref name=nris/>\n\nThe parish is part of the [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America]] in the [[Episcopal Diocese of Long Island]], part of the worldwide [[Anglican Communion]], in the [[Anglo-Catholic]] tradition.\n\n== Parish history ==\nSt. Paul's was founded on Christmas Day of 1849, in [[South Brooklyn]], then the quickly developing southward expansion of old [[Brooklyn Heights]]. New homes and businesses were covering old countryside, farmland, and shoreline; [[industrialization]] was bringing a new way of life to the [[City of Brooklyn]], waves of immigrants from the nations of the world were arriving and the [[American Civil War]] was looming.  This was also the era when the [[Anglican Communion]] of Churches was experiencing a renewed vision of their catholic faith and order often called the \"Anglo-Catholic Revival\" of the [[Oxford Movement]]. Saint Paul's was formed in heady days of philosophical, social, economic, and religious change.<ref name=\"nrhpinv_ny\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3330|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration:St. Paul's Protestant Episcopal Church|date=October 1989|accessdate=2011-02-20 |author=Kathleen LaFrank|publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]}} ''See also:'' {{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3331|title=Accompanying six photos}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*{{Portal-inline|Christianity}}\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline|St. Paul's Episcopal Church (Brooklyn, New York)}}\n*[http://www.stpaulscarrollst.org/ Official website]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Pauls Church, Brooklyn}}\n[[Category:Properties of religious function on the National Register of Historic Places in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival church buildings in New York City]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1866]]\n[[Category:19th-century Episcopal church buildings]]\n[[Category:Churches in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Catholic church buildings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Episcopal church buildings in New York City]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Culture of Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Richard Michell Upjohn church buildings]]\n[[Category:Richard Upjohn church buildings]]\n[[Category:Carroll Gardens, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:1866 establishments in New York (state)]]\n\n\n{{Brooklyn-NRHP-stub}}\n{{Brooklyn-church-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wlogburn", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Paul%27s_Episcopal_Church_(Brooklyn)"}
{"title_page": "Shelby Starner", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Shelby Starner\n| image            = Shelby Starner.jpg\n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Shelby E. Starner\n| alias            = \n| birth_place      = [[East Stroudsburg, Pennsylvania|East Stroudsburg]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|mf=yes|1984|01|3}}\n| death_place      = [[Bartonsville, Pennsylvania|Bartonsville]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|mf=yes|2003|06|22|1984|01|03}}\n| instrument       = Vocals, piano\n| background       = solo_singer\n| occupation       = Musician, songwriter\n| years_active     = 1997\u20132002\n| genre            = Pop\n| label            = [[Warner Bros. Records]]\n}}\n\n'''Shelby E. Starner''' (January 3, 1984 \u2013 June 22, 2003) was an American singer-songwriter and musician. She signed a record deal with [[Warner Bros. Records]] in 1997, releasing her official debut single, \"Don't Let Them\"  two years later. Starner released her debut studio album, ''[[From in the Shadows]]'', later in 1999, but it was not commercially successful. In 2000, Starner worked on a second album; it was never released. Unhappy with Warner Bros. Records, Starner ended her contract. On June 22, 2003, Starner died suddenly at her home due to complications from [[bulimia nervosa]].\n\n== Early life ==\nShelby E. Starner was born January 3, 1984,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/93783697/shelby-e.-starner#view-photo=63724063|title=Shelby E. Starner (1984\u20132003) |website=www.findagrave.com|access-date=May 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627091015/https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/93783697/shelby-e.-starner#view-photo=63724063|archive-date=June 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> in [[East Stroudsburg, Pennsylvania]], to Katherine Hass and Ray J. Starner. She had a stepmother, Susan LaRose, and a stepfather, Allen Benn, in addition to her younger sister, Emily P. Benn, and stepbrother Willie LaRose.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17318395/shelby_e_starner/|title=Shelby E. Starner|last=|first=|date=June 24, 2003|work=[[The Morning Call]]|access-date=May 3, 2018|location=Allentown, Pennsylvania|page=18|language=en|via=Newspapers.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504091429/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17318395/shelby_e_starner/|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Starner resided in [[Bartonsville, Pennsylvania|Bartonsville]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.poconorecord.com/article/20030629/news/306299999|title=Psychological problem becomes physical when eating habits get out of hand|last=Amerman|first=Kevin|date=June 29, 2003|work=[[Pocono Record]]|access-date=May 3, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504090919/http://www.poconorecord.com/article/20030629/news/306299999|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She began writing poetry and songs at the age of 11.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 1996\u20131998: Career beginnings ===\nAt 12 years of age, Starner wrote the first song she deemed \"acceptable\" called \"Straight A Student.\" In it, she sang about a popular 17-year-old friend who died when he was driving drunk.<ref name=\":2\" /> Later, in December 1996, Starner's father gifted her a three hour slot at a studio<ref name=\":2\" /> where she recorded four [[Demo (music)|demos]] of original songs.<ref name=\":3\" /> Starner was embarrassed initially but later enjoyed the experience.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/1999/mar/01/gender.uk|title=The real thing|last=O'Brien|first=Lucy|date=March 1, 1999|website=[[The Guardian]]|language=en|access-date=May 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627062336/https://www.theguardian.com/world/1999/mar/01/gender.uk|archive-date=June 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A lawyer and friend of the family gave the demo to executives at [[Warner Bros. Records]]. In December 1997, Starner signed her a record deal with Warner Bros.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> It consisted of a six-album contract worth more than $5 million.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Deconstructing Sammy music, money, madness, and the mob|first=Matt|last=Birkbeck|date=2009|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|isbn=9780061982415|location=[New York]|oclc=937843081}}</ref> Her press representative was Liz Rosenberg, the then senior vice president of publicity at Warner.<ref name=\":2\" /> She enrolled in a [[Homeschooling|home school]] program for her freshman year of high school.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stout|first=Alan K.|author-link=Alan K. Stout|date=March 12, 1999|title=15-year-old singer/composer Shelby Starner creates a buzz in music industry.|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-54084558.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180506035429/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-54084558.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=May 6, 2018|journal=Knight Ridder/Tribune News Service|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam}}</ref>\n\n=== 1999: ''From in the Shadows'' ===\nStarner recorded a music video for her first single, \"Don't Let Them\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://articles.mcall.com/1999-04-10/entertainment/3256286_1_mmm-songs-liz-rosenberg|title=She's 15, She's A Hit, She's From The Poconos|last=Frassinelli|first=Mike|date=April 10, 1999|work=[[The Morning Call]]|access-date=May 3, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504091258/http://articles.mcall.com/1999-04-10/entertainment/3256286_1_mmm-songs-liz-rosenberg|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She released her debut album ''[[From in the Shadows]]'', in 1999, through Warner Bros. Records. It was met with positive acclaim but was not commercially successful.<ref name=\":1\" /> Produced by [[Craig Street]], it featured 13 songs.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19785572/the_philadelphia_inquirer/|title=Interesting structures support Starner's songs|last=Moon|first=Tom|date=March 28, 1999|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|access-date=May 3, 2018|page=86|language=en|author-link=Tom Moon|via=Newspapers.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504090758/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19785572/the_philadelphia_inquirer/|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Starner's song about the lack of trust and loyalty in a relationship entitled \"You\", was featured in commercials for ''[[Dawson's Creek]]''.<ref name=\":2\" /> She received coverage in ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', ''[[Newsweek]]'', and ''[[USA Today]]'' and appeared on ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]''.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gw4EAAAAMBAJ|title=WBs Starner Emerges|last=Flick|first=Larry|date=February 13, 1999|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|volume=111|pages=|language=en|issn=0006-2510|issue=7}}</ref> ''Newsweek'' praised Starner as a \"pop prodigy\".<ref>{{Cite journal|date=January 25, 1999|title=New Faces of '99|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-53612346.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180506173442/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-53612346.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=May 6, 2018|journal=[[Newsweek]]|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam}}</ref> In February 1999, ''Billboard'' announced that Starner would be going on a small concert tour through the United States in mid-spring and that Monterey Peninsula Artists was the booking agency.<ref name=\":7\" />  In April 1999, Starner began a mini-concert tour through the [[Far East]] and Australia, after which a full United States tour was planned.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19797675/the_philadelphia_inquirer/|title=Age aside, an artist|last=Moon|first=Tom|date=March 28, 1999|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|access-date=May 4, 2018|page=F11|language=en|author-link=Tom Moon|via=Newspapers.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627091137/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19797675/the_philadelphia_inquirer/|archive-date=June 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In Australia, she appeared on an episode of ''[[Hey Hey It's Saturday]]'' with host [[Larry Emdur]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19798055/the_age/|title=Saturday TV|last=Warneke|first=Ross|date=April 24, 1999|work=[[The Age]]|access-date=May 4, 2018|location=Australia|language=en|author-link=Ross Warneke|via=Newspapers.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627091108/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19798055/the_age/|archive-date=June 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 2000: Second album and hiatus ===\nIn 2000, Starner began work on her second album with members of the [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]]. She wanted to move into [[rock and roll]], but she did not release the album and chose instead to drop her contract with Warner Bros. Starner's mother commented that, \"Warner Brothers wasn't creative enough to find a niche for her ... She was a little mellow and thought of things a little too deeply compared to kids her age that listened to the radio.\" Starner and her family initially intended to find another company for her to start over until her mother was diagnosed with breast cancer. As a result of these family health issues, Starner did not want to leave her younger sister. During this time, Starner was interested in [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.poconorecord.com/article/20030624/News/306249996|title=Music prodigy loses life to eating disorder|last=Amerman|first=Kevin|date=June 24, 2003|work=[[Pocono Record]]|access-date=May 4, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504225323/http://www.poconorecord.com/article/20030624/News/306249996|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Starner planned on enrolling at the [[University of Pittsburgh]] in August 2003 to [[Major (academia)|major]] in [[Latin American studies|Latin-American studies]] and writing.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> She aspired to write and have an essay on [[Bulimia nervosa|bulimia]] published.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nStarner worked at the Everybody's Cafe on Main Street in Stroudsburg during the months leading up to her death.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Artistry ==\nMusic critic [[Tom Moon]] praised her debut album ''From in the Shadows'', saying it contained \"...{{nbsp}}powerfully revelatory songs, with lyrics that alternate between the scribbled journal entries of a tetchy teenager and the thoughtful, disarming observations of an adult.\"<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1049616|title=Shelby Starner|work=NPR.org|access-date=May 4, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627115704/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1049616|archive-date=June 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A ''USA Today'' article stated, \"folky debut album 'From the Shadows' got good notices last year (1999), but made little commercial headway.\"<ref name=\":5\" /> Starner's pop-folk voice has been compared to [[Jewel (singer)|Jewel]] and [[Tori Amos]].<ref name=\":2\" /> In January 1999, Jonathan Bernstein, a film critic at ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'', wrote that Shelby Starner and Britney Spears \"make up the front line of the next assault of girl-teen prodigies.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YG5YubNw1pgC&pg=PA38|title=Little Darlings|last=Bernstein|first=Jonathan|journal=Spin|date=January 1999|publisher=[[SpinMedia]] LLC|volume=15|pages=38|language=en|issn=0886-3032|issue=1}}</ref> Record producer, [[Jim Scott (producer)|Jim Scott]], said that: \"Out of all the young artists I've worked with, she was the most spectacular: a great great artist.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/behindglasstopre00mass/page/90|title=Behind the glass: top record producers tell how they craft the hits|first=Howard|last=Massey|date=2000|publisher=[[Miller Freeman Books]]|isbn=0879306149|location=San Francisco|page=[https://archive.org/details/behindglasstopre00mass/page/90 90]|oclc=44573266|url-access=registration}}</ref> Starner acknowledged [[Janis Joplin]] was her role model.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==Death==\nAccording to her mother, Starner learned how to hide symptoms of [[Bulimia nervosa|bulimia]] by reading websites that promoted it as a lifestyle.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Prah|first=Pamela M.|date=February 2006|title=Eating Disorders: Is societal pressure to be thin to blame?|url=http://library.cqpress.com/cqresearcher/document.php?id=cqresrre2006021000|journal=[[CQ Press|CQ Researcher]]|language=en|publisher=CQ Press|volume=16|issue=6|pages=|issn=1942-5635|url-access=subscription|access-date=November 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180505065656/http://library.cqpress.com/cqresearcher/document.php?id=cqresrre2006021000|archive-date=May 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On June 22, 2003, Starner died at her home. She had bulimia-related [[electrolyte imbalance]], that caused brain swelling resulting in a stroke and seizure. Attempts to revive her at the [[Pocono Medical Center]] were unsuccessful.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/27/kathy-benn-petition-google-thinspo_n_3503773.html|title=Kathy Benn, Mother Who Lost Daughter To Bulimia, Petitions Google To Combat Thinspo|last=Johnson|first=Margaret Wheeler|date=June 27, 2013|work=[[Huffington Post]]|access-date=May 4, 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320012856/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/27/kathy-benn-petition-google-thinspo_n_3503773.html|archive-date=March 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Studio albums ===\n* ''[[From in the Shadows]]'' Released: April 6,&nbsp;1999<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lVwOt5tiDncC|title=CMJ New Music Report|date=April 12, 1999|publisher=CMJ Network|language=en}}</ref> \n*:Label: Warner Bros. Records. Formats: CD, cassette\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Starner, Shelby}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American child singers]]\n[[Category:American child musicians]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American female pop singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:People from East Stroudsburg, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Singers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh people]]\n[[Category:Warner Records artists]]\n[[Category:Neurological disease deaths in the United States]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Shelby Starner\n| image            = Shelby Starner.jpg\n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Shelby E. Starner\n| alias            = \n| birth_place      = [[East Stroudsburg, Pennsylvania|East Stroudsburg]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|mf=yes|1984|01|3}}\n| death_place      = [[Bartonsville, Pennsylvania|Bartonsville]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|mf=yes|2003|06|22|1984|01|03}}\n| instrument       = Vocals, piano\n| background       = solo_singer\n| occupation       = Musician, songwriter\n| years_active     = 1997\u20132002\n| genre            = Pop\n| label            = [[Warner Bros. Records]]\n}}\n\n'''Shelby E. Starner''' (January 3, 1984 \u2013 June 22, 2003) was an American singer-songwriter and musician. She signed a record deal with [[Warner Bros. Records]] in 1997, releasing her official debut single, \"Don't Let Them\"  two years later. Starner released her debut studio album, ''[[From in the Shadows]]'', later in 1999, but it was not commercially successful. In 2000, Starner worked on a second album; it was never released. Unhappy with Warner Bros. Records, Starner ended her contract. On June 22, 2003, Starner died suddenly at her home due to complications from [[bulimia nervosa]].\n\n== Early life ==\nShelby E. Starner was born January 3, 1984,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/93783697/shelby-e.-starner#view-photo=63724063|title=Shelby E. Starner (1984\u20132003) |website=www.findagrave.com|access-date=May 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627091015/https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/93783697/shelby-e.-starner#view-photo=63724063|archive-date=June 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> in [[East Stroudsburg, Pennsylvania]], to Katherine Hass and Ray J. Starner. She had a stepmother, Susan LaRose, and a stepfather, Allen Benn, in addition to her younger sister, Emily P. Benn, and stepbrother Willie LaRose.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17318395/shelby_e_starner/|title=Shelby E. Starner|last=|first=|date=June 24, 2003|work=[[The Morning Call]]|access-date=May 3, 2018|location=Allentown, Pennsylvania|page=18|language=en|via=Newspapers.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504091429/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17318395/shelby_e_starner/|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Starner resided in [[Bartonsville, Pennsylvania|Bartonsville]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.poconorecord.com/article/20030629/news/306299999|title=Psychological problem becomes physical when eating habits get out of hand|last=Amerman|first=Kevin|date=2003-06-29|work=[[Pocono Record]]|access-date=May 3, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504090919/http://www.poconorecord.com/article/20030629/news/306299999|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She began writing poetry and songs at the age of 11.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 1996\u20131998: Career beginnings ===\nAt 12 years of age, Starner wrote the first song she deemed \"acceptable\" called \"Straight A Student.\" In it, she sang about a popular 17-year-old friend who died when he was driving drunk.<ref name=\":2\" /> Later, in December 1996, Starner's father gifted her a three hour slot at a studio<ref name=\":2\" /> where she recorded four [[Demo (music)|demos]] of original songs.<ref name=\":3\" /> Starner was embarrassed initially but later enjoyed the experience.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/1999/mar/01/gender.uk|title=The real thing|last=O'Brien|first=Lucy|date=1999-03-01|website=[[The Guardian]]|language=en|access-date=May 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627062336/https://www.theguardian.com/world/1999/mar/01/gender.uk|archive-date=June 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A lawyer and friend of the family gave the demo to executives at [[Warner Bros. Records]]. In December 1997, Starner signed her a record deal with Warner Bros.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> It consisted of a six-album contract worth more than $5 million.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Deconstructing Sammy music, money, madness, and the mob|first=Matt|last=Birkbeck|date=2009|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|isbn=9780061982415|location=[New York]|oclc=937843081}}</ref> Her press representative was Liz Rosenberg, the then senior vice president of publicity at Warner.<ref name=\":2\" /> She enrolled in a [[Homeschooling|home school]] program for her freshman year of high school.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stout|first=Alan K.|author-link=Alan K. Stout|date=1999-03-12|title=15-year-old singer/composer Shelby Starner creates a buzz in music industry.|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-54084558.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180506035429/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-54084558.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=May 6, 2018|journal=Knight Ridder/Tribune News Service|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam}}</ref>\n\n=== 1999: ''From in the Shadows'' ===\nStarner recorded a music video for her first single, \"Don't Let Them\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://articles.mcall.com/1999-04-10/entertainment/3256286_1_mmm-songs-liz-rosenberg|title=She's 15, She's A Hit, She's From The Poconos|last=Frassinelli|first=Mike|date=1999-04-10|work=[[The Morning Call]]|access-date=May 3, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504091258/http://articles.mcall.com/1999-04-10/entertainment/3256286_1_mmm-songs-liz-rosenberg|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She released her debut album ''[[From in the Shadows]]'', in 1999, through Warner Bros. Records. It was met with positive acclaim but was not commercially successful.<ref name=\":1\" /> Produced by [[Craig Street]], it featured 13 songs.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19785572/the_philadelphia_inquirer/|title=Interesting structures support Starner's songs|last=Moon|first=Tom|date=March 28, 1999|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|access-date=May 3, 2018|page=86|language=en|author-link=Tom Moon|via=Newspapers.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504090758/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19785572/the_philadelphia_inquirer/|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Starner's song about the lack of trust and loyalty in a relationship entitled \"You\", was featured in commercials for ''[[Dawson's Creek]]''.<ref name=\":2\" /> She received coverage in ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', ''[[Newsweek]]'', and ''[[USA Today]]'' and appeared on ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]''.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gw4EAAAAMBAJ|title=WBs Starner Emerges|last=Flick|first=Larry|date=February 13, 1999|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|volume=111|pages=|language=en|issn=0006-2510|issue=7}}</ref> ''Newsweek'' praised Starner as a \"pop prodigy\".<ref>{{Cite journal|date=January 25, 1999|title=New Faces of '99|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-53612346.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180506173442/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-53612346.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=May 6, 2018|journal=[[Newsweek]]|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam}}</ref> In February 1999, ''Billboard'' announced that Starner would be going on a small concert tour through the United States in mid-spring and that Monterey Peninsula Artists was the booking agency.<ref name=\":7\" />  In April 1999, Starner began a mini-concert tour through the [[Far East]] and Australia, after which a full United States tour was planned.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19797675/the_philadelphia_inquirer/|title=Age aside, an artist|last=Moon|first=Tom|date=March 28, 1999|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|access-date=May 4, 2018|page=F11|language=en|author-link=Tom Moon|via=Newspapers.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627091137/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19797675/the_philadelphia_inquirer/|archive-date=June 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In Australia, she appeared on an episode of ''[[Hey Hey It's Saturday]]'' with host [[Larry Emdur]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19798055/the_age/|title=Saturday TV|last=Warneke|first=Ross|date=1999-04-24|work=[[The Age]]|access-date=May 4, 2018|location=Australia|language=en|author-link=Ross Warneke|via=Newspapers.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627091108/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19798055/the_age/|archive-date=June 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 2000: Second album and hiatus ===\nIn 2000, Starner began work on her second album with members of the [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]]. She wanted to move into [[rock and roll]], but she did not release the album and chose instead to drop her contract with Warner Bros. Starner's mother commented that, \"Warner Brothers wasn't creative enough to find a niche for her ... She was a little mellow and thought of things a little too deeply compared to kids her age that listened to the radio.\" Starner and her family initially intended to find another company for her to start over until her mother was diagnosed with breast cancer. As a result of these family health issues, Starner did not want to leave her younger sister. During this time, Starner was interested in [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.poconorecord.com/article/20030624/News/306249996|title=Music prodigy loses life to eating disorder|last=Amerman|first=Kevin|date=2003-06-24|work=[[Pocono Record]]|access-date=May 4, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504225323/http://www.poconorecord.com/article/20030624/News/306249996|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Starner planned on enrolling at the [[University of Pittsburgh]] in August 2003 to [[Major (academia)|major]] in [[Latin American studies|Latin-American studies]] and writing.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> She aspired to write and have an essay on [[Bulimia nervosa|bulimia]] published.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nStarner worked at the Everybody's Cafe on Main Street in Stroudsburg during the months leading up to her death.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Artistry ==\nMusic critic [[Tom Moon]] praised her debut album ''From in the Shadows'', saying it contained \"...{{nbsp}}powerfully revelatory songs, with lyrics that alternate between the scribbled journal entries of a tetchy teenager and the thoughtful, disarming observations of an adult.\"<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1049616|title=Shelby Starner|work=NPR.org|access-date=May 4, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627115704/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1049616|archive-date=June 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A ''USA Today'' article stated, \"folky debut album 'From the Shadows' got good notices last year (1999), but made little commercial headway.\"<ref name=\":5\" /> Starner's pop-folk voice has been compared to [[Jewel (singer)|Jewel]] and [[Tori Amos]].<ref name=\":2\" /> In January 1999, Jonathan Bernstein, a film critic at ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'', wrote that Shelby Starner and Britney Spears \"make up the front line of the next assault of girl-teen prodigies.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YG5YubNw1pgC&pg=PA38|title=Little Darlings|last=Bernstein|first=Jonathan|journal=Spin|date=January 1999|publisher=[[SpinMedia]] LLC|volume=15|pages=38|language=en|issn=0886-3032|issue=1}}</ref> Record producer, [[Jim Scott (producer)|Jim Scott]], said that: \"Out of all the young artists I've worked with, she was the most spectacular: a great great artist.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/behindglasstopre00mass/page/90|title=Behind the glass: top record producers tell how they craft the hits|first=Howard|last=Massey|date=2000|publisher=[[Miller Freeman Books]]|isbn=0879306149|location=San Francisco|page=[https://archive.org/details/behindglasstopre00mass/page/90 90]|oclc=44573266|url-access=registration}}</ref> Starner acknowledged [[Janis Joplin]] was her role model.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==Death==\nAccording to her mother, Starner learned how to hide symptoms of [[Bulimia nervosa|bulimia]] by reading websites that promoted it as a lifestyle.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Prah|first=Pamela M.|date=February 2006|title=Eating Disorders: Is societal pressure to be thin to blame?|url=http://library.cqpress.com/cqresearcher/document.php?id=cqresrre2006021000|journal=[[CQ Press|CQ Researcher]]|language=en|publisher=CQ Press|volume=16|issue=6|pages=|issn=1942-5635|url-access=subscription|access-date=November 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180505065656/http://library.cqpress.com/cqresearcher/document.php?id=cqresrre2006021000|archive-date=May 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On June 22, 2003, Starner died at her home. She had bulimia-related [[electrolyte imbalance]], that caused brain swelling resulting in a stroke and seizure. Attempts to revive her at the [[Pocono Medical Center]] were unsuccessful.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/27/kathy-benn-petition-google-thinspo_n_3503773.html|title=Kathy Benn, Mother Who Lost Daughter To Bulimia, Petitions Google To Combat Thinspo|last=Johnson|first=Margaret Wheeler|date=June 27, 2013|work=[[Huffington Post]]|access-date=May 4, 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320012856/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/27/kathy-benn-petition-google-thinspo_n_3503773.html|archive-date=March 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Studio albums ===\n* ''[[From in the Shadows]]'' Released: April 6,&nbsp;1999<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lVwOt5tiDncC|title=CMJ New Music Report|date=1999-04-12|publisher=CMJ Network|language=en}}</ref> \n*:Label: Warner Bros. Records. Formats: CD, cassette\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Starner, Shelby}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American child singers]]\n[[Category:American child musicians]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American female pop singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:People from East Stroudsburg, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Singers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh people]]\n[[Category:Warner Records artists]]\n[[Category:Neurological disease deaths in the United States]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "The Rambling Man", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelby_Starner"}
{"title_page": "Google Stadia", "text_new": "{{short description|Google cloud gaming/streaming service}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox online service\n| name               = Stadia\n| logo = [[File:Stadia logo.svg|frameless|upright=0.4]]<br /><div style=\"margin-top:5px\">[[File:Stadia Wordmark.svg|frameless|upright=0.85]]</div>\n| logo_alt           = Logo for Stadia\n| image              = [[File:Google Stadia Cloud gaming (48605754611).jpg|200px]]\n| caption            = Mobile device running ''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]'' on Stadia with official controller\n| developer          = [[Google]]\n| launched           = {{start date and age|2019|11|19}}<!--Founder's Edition & Premiere Edition-->\n| operating system   = [[Cross-platform software|Cross-platform]]\n| Users              =\n| website            = {{URL|https://stadia.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Stadia''' is a [[cloud gaming]] service operated by [[Google]]. It is advertised to be capable of streaming video games up to [[4K resolution]] at 60 [[Frame rate|frames per second]] with support for [[High-dynamic-range video|high-dynamic-range]], to players via the company's numerous data centers across the globe, provided they are using a sufficiently high-speed Internet connection. It is accessible through the [[Google Chrome]] web browser on desktop computers, [[Pixel (smartphone)|Pixel smartphones]], supported smartphones from Samsung, Razer and Asus<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://community.stadia.com/t5/Stadia-Community-Blog/This-Week-on-Stadia-Play-games-on-tens-of-millions-of-new-phones/ba-p/15326|title=This Week on Stadia: Play games on tens of millions of new phones|date=2020-02-18|website=community.stadia.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>, as well as [[Chrome OS]] tablets and [[Chromecast]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://support.google.com/stadia/answer/9338946?hl=en |title=Stadia FAQ |website=Stadia Help |publisher=Google |date=June 20, 2019 |access-date=July 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe service is planned to be integrated with [[YouTube]], and its \"state share\" feature will allow viewers of a Stadia stream to launch a game on the service on the same [[Saved game#Save states|save state]] as the streamer. This has been used as a [[Unique selling proposition|selling point]] for the service. It is compatible with [[USB human interface device class|HID class USB]] controllers, though a proprietary controller manufactured by Google with a direct Wi-Fi link to data centers is available alongside the service. Despite comparisons, Stadia is not similar to [[Netflix]], in that Stadia requires users to purchase games to stream via Stadia rather than pay for access to a library of games. While the base service is free, a [[premium business model|Pro tier]] monthly subscription allows users to stream at higher rates of upto [[4K resolution]], surround sound, and offers 1-3 free games a month that the user has access to while they are subscribed to Pro with or without gaps.\n\nKnown in development as '''Project Stream''', the service was debuted through a [[Software release life cycle#Open and closed beta|closed beta]] running ''[[Assassin's Creed Odyssey]]'' in October 2018. Stadia was publicly released on November 19, 2019 in selected countries and received a mixed reception from reviewers. The service competes with [[Sony Interactive Entertainment|Sony]]'s [[PlayStation Now]] service, [[Nvidia]]'s [[GeForce Now]], and [[Microsoft]]'s [[XCloud|Project xCloud]]. On 8 April, 2020 Google started rolling out Stadia free base service, along with giving new users two months of Pro subscription.\n\n== Features ==\nStadia is a cloud gaming service,<ref name=\"HighlyTechno\" /> and does not require additional computer hardware, only requiring the device to have an Internet connection and support for [[Google Chrome]]. Stadia works atop [[YouTube]]'s functionality in streaming media to the user, as game streaming is seen as an extension of watching [[Video game live streaming|video game live streams]], according to Google's [[Phil Harrison]]; the name \"Stadia\", the Latin plural of \"stadium\", is meant to reflect that it is a collection of entertainment, which the viewer can choose to sit back and watch, or take an active part in.<ref name=\"eu interview\">{{cite web | url = https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/digitalfoundry-2019-google-stadia-phil-harrison-majd-bakar-interview |title = The big interview: Phil Harrison and Majd Bakar on Google Stadia | first = Richard | last= Leadbetter | date = March 19, 2019 | access-date = March 19, 2019 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> As Google had built out a large number of data centers across the globe, the company believes that Stadia is in a better position for cloud gaming compared to past endeavours like [[OnLive]], [[PlayStation Now]], and [[Gaikai]], as most players would be geographically close to a data center. Stadia supports the streaming of games in [[High-dynamic-range video|HDR]] at 60 frames per second with [[4K resolution]], and anticipates eventually reaching 120 frames per second at [[8K resolution]].<ref name=\"eu interview\" /> Players can start games without having to download new content to their personal device. Players can opt to record or stream their sessions onto YouTube through Stadia. Viewers of such streams can launch the games directly from the stream with the same save state that they were just watching.<ref name=\"eu interview\" />\n\nThe streaming technology enables new features on Stadia. Stream Connect allows Stadia players, cooperatively playing the same game with friends, to have [[picture-in-picture]] inserts on their display of their friends' point-of-view in the game. This feature was first launched with the release of ''[[Tom Clancy's Ghost Recon Breakpoint]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.vg247.com/2019/12/17/stadia-ghost-recon-breakpoint-first-stream-connect-game/ | title = Stadia\u2019s first Stream Connect game, Ghost Recon Breakpoint, arrives tomorrow | first = Sherif | last = Saed | date = December 17, 2019 | accessdate = December 17, 2019 | work = [[VG247]] }}</ref> The streaming technology allows for larger number of concurrent players on a game server; for example, servers for ''[[Grid (2019 video game)|Grid]]'' are normally limited to 16 players, while the Stadia version will allow up to 40.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamer.com/grid-for-stadia-has-a-40-car-mode-that-isnt-possible-with-other-hardware/ | title = Grid for Stadia has a 40 car mode that 'isn't possible with other hardware' | first= Shaun  |last = Prescott | date=  November 23, 2019 | accessdate = December 17, 2019 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref>\n\nWhile Stadia can use any [[USB human interface device class|HID-class]] [[USB]] controller, Google developed its own controller which connects via Wi-Fi directly to the Google data center in which the game is running, to reduce input latency.<ref name=\"eu interview\" /> Google is also exploring further ways to reduce latency, using an idea called \"negative latency\" which involves prediction of user input through various means so that any apparent network lag between controller and game response is minimized.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.engadget.com/2019/10/10/google-stadia-negative-latency/ | title = Google wants to reduce Stadia lag with 'negative latency' | first=  Marc | last= DeAngelis | date = October 10, 2019 | accessdate = October 10, 2019  |work = [[Engadget]]}}</ref> During its GDC 2019 keynote reveal, Google confirmed that the controller would also feature [[Google Assistant]], which will automatically search YouTube for relevant, helpful videos related to the game they are currently playing at the touch of a key.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gameskinny.com/1hak5/stadias-wi-fi-controller-looks-familiar-but-features-google-assistant|title=Stadia's Wi-Fi Controller Looks Familiar, But Features Google Assistant|first=Quintlyn|last=Bowers|work=GameSkinny|date=March 19, 2019|accessdate=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nStadia offers two tiers of service, a free Base level and a monthly subscription Pro level. The Pro tier costs approximately {{USD|10}} per month, but allows users to access higher streaming rates, access a library of free games over time, and get discounts on other games offered for Stadia.<ref name=\"verge\" /> Harrison stated they are also looking into offering publisher subscriptions and other models in the future;<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2019/06/09/google-stadia-publisher-subscriptions/ | title= Google Stadia's getting publisher subscriptions on top of Stadia Pro | first=  Katherine | last =Castle | date = June 9, 2019 | access-date = June 9, 2019 | work = [[Rock Paper Shotgun]] }}</ref> for example, [[Ubisoft]] announced its Uplay Plus subscription service will be available to Stadia users.\n\nThe internet speed requirements for the different types of picture quality from Stadia's service is as follows:<ref>{{cite web |title=Stadia Founder's Edition |url=https://store.google.com/product/stadia_founders_edition |website=Google Store |accessdate=26 June 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626230111/https://store.google.com/product/stadia_founders_edition |archivedate=26 June 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Speedtest |url=https://projectstream.google.com/speedtest |website=Google Store |accessdate=26 June 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626214359/https://projectstream.google.com/speedtest |archivedate=26 June 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Bandwidth required\n!Video quality\n!Audio quality\n|-\n|10 MBit/s\n|[[720p]], 60{{nbsp}}[[Frame rate|FPS]]\n|[[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n|-\n|20 MBit/s\n|[[1080p]] [[High-dynamic-range video|HDR Video]], 60{{nbsp}}FPS\n|[[5.1 surround sound|5.1 Surround]]\n|-\n|35 MBit/s\n|[[4K resolution|4K]] HDR Video, 60{{nbsp}}FPS\n|5.1 Surround\n|}\n\n== Hardware ==\nUpon launch, Stadia's cloud hardware initially uses a custom [[Intel]]<ref name=\"extremetech-1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.extremetech.com/gaming/288237-google-stadia-is-powered-by-intel-cpus-not-amd|title=Google Stadia is powered by Intel, not AMD|first=Joel|last=Hruska|date=March 25, 2019|accessdate=March 26, 2019|work=[[ExtremeTech]]}}</ref> [[x86]] processor clocked at 2.7&nbsp;GHz, with [[Advanced Vector Extensions|AVX2]] and 9.5 megabytes of L2+L3 cache.<ref name=\"pcgamer-1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/google-stadias-specs-and-latency-revealed/|title=Google Stadia's specs and latency revealed|first=Paul|last=Lilly|date=March 19, 2019|accessdate=March 26, 2019|work=[[PC Gamer]]}}</ref> It also uses a custom [[Advanced Micro Devices|AMD]] [[graphics processing unit|GPU]] based on the [[Radeon RX Vega series|Vega]] architecture with [[High Bandwidth Memory|HBM2]] memory, 56 compute units, and 10.7 [[FLOPS|teraFLOPS]].<ref name=\"pcgamer-1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.notebookcheck.net/Google-Stadia-uses-a-custom-AMD-Vega-56-GCN-1-5-GPU.421131.0.html|title=Google Stadia uses a custom AMD Vega 56 GCN 1.5 GPU|last=Subramaniam|first=Vaidyanathan|website=Notebookcheck|language=en|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref> The service also has [[solid-state drive]] storage, and 16&nbsp;GB of [[random-access memory|RAM]] (supporting up to 484&nbsp;GB/s bandwidth) shared between the GPU and the [[Central processing unit|CPU]].<ref name=\"pcgamer-1\" />\n\nGoogle developed the controller for Stadia. The controller includes two thumbsticks, a directional pad, four main face buttons, two sets of shoulder buttons, and five additional controller face buttons. The controller has the capability of connection over a wireless network, rather than through the device that the user is playing on, as to reduce the latency of controller communication with Stadia services. The controller is available in a variation of four colors at its launch.<ref name=\"verge\" />\n\nStadia initially launched in November 19, 2019 with a Founder's Pack, which included a [[Chromecast Ultra]], a Stadia controller, three months of Pro service, and an additional three months of Pro service to gift to a friend.<ref name=\"verge\" /><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/10/15/20908177/google-stadia-release-date-founders-edition-pixel-4-event | title = Google\u2019s Stadia cloud gaming service will launch on November 19th | first = Sean | last = Hollister | date = October 15, 2019 | accessdate = October 15, 2019 | work = [[The Verge]] }}</ref>\n\nThe service was expanded to several [[Samsung Galaxy]], [[Razer Phone]] and [[ASUS]] [[ROG Phone]] devices in February 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.videogameschronicle.com/news/stadia-expanding-android-mobile-support-this-week/ | title = Stadia expanding Android mobile support this week | first = Tom | last =Ivan | date = February 18, 2020 | accessdate = February 18, 2020 | work =[[Video Games Chronicle]] }}</ref>\n\n== Software ==\nStadia is built on [[Debian]] [[Linux]] servers and [[Vulkan (API)|Vulkan]] is their graphics API.<ref name=\"Welcome to Stadia\">{{cite web |title=Welcome to Stadia |url=https://stadia.dev/blog/welcome-to-stadia |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Stadia Is Google's Cloud Gaming Service Using Linux, Vulkan & A Custom AMD GPU |url=https://www.phoronix.com/scan.php?page=news_item&px=Google-Stadia-Vulkan-Linux |publisher=[[phoronix.com]] |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{quote\n| \"This [Stadia] starts with our platform foundations of Linux and Vulkan and shows in our selection of GPUs that have open-source drivers and tools. We\u2019re integrating [[LLVM]] and DirectX Shader Compiler to ensure you get great features and performance from our compilers and debuggers.\"<ref name=\"Welcome to Stadia\" />\n| Dov Zimring, Stadia Developer Platform Lead\n}}\n\n== Development ==\n[[File:Google Stadia GDC 2019.jpg|thumb|right|Stadia booth at the 2019 [[Game Developers Conference]].]]\nProject Stream was Google's first announced sign of interest in video gaming products. The company had previously been rumored as working on a service called Project Yeti since at least 2016. Google had also hired gaming industry executive [[Phil Harrison]] and was seen recruiting developers during industry events in 2018.{{r|Ars T announce}} Project Stream's main differentiator from past services, such as [[OnLive]], [[GeForce Now]], and [[PlayStation Now]], is its ability to run in any desktop Chrome browser, so no additional software needs to be installed.{{r|Ars T preview}} The service uses [[Advanced Micro Devices|AMD]] [[Radeon]] [[graphics processing units|graphics hardware]].<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Takahashi |first1=Dean |title=Google's Project Stream cloud gaming will use AMD Radeon Graphics |work=[[VentureBeat]] |date=2019-01-09 |url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/01/09/googles-project-stream-cloud-gaming-will-use-amd-radeon-graphics/ |accessdate=2019-01-13 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Internally, the service was developed around 2016's ''[[Doom (2016 video game)|Doom]]'' to show that the proof-of-concept worked in realistic settings across the public internet.<ref>{{cite video | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ApbhHzYTyNo | title = How DOOM Helped Convince Google That Stadia Would Work \u2013 IGN First | date = November 8, 2019 | accessdate = November 8, 2019 | work = [[IGN]] | via = [[YouTube]] }}</ref>\n\nGoogle announced the service in October 2018{{r|Polygon preview}} and soon after, opened invitations to beta testers with access to ''[[Assassin's Creed Odyssey]]''. Players could apply for access and those who met an Internet speed minimum could run the game in their Chrome browsers.{{r|Verge preview}} Those who participated received a free copy of the game when the beta expired.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Good |first1=Owen S. |title=Get free Assassin\u2019s Creed Odyssey on PC for testing Google\u2019s Project Stream |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=2018-12-15 |url=https://www.polygon.com/pc/2018/12/15/18142147/assassins-creed-odyssey-free-pc-google-project-stream |accessdate=2019-01-01 |df=mdy-all |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181223140009/https://www.polygon.com/pc/2018/12/15/18142147/assassins-creed-odyssey-free-pc-google-project-stream |archive-date=December 23, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Stadia was formally announced during Google's keynote address at the 2019 [[Game Developers Conference]] in March 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamer.com/google-announces-stadia-a-streaming-service-to-make-games-available-for-everyone/ | title = Google announces Stadia, a game streaming service 'for everyone' | first= Tyler | last= Wilde | date = March 19, 2019 | accessdate = March 19, 2019 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref> To support Stadia, Google also announced the formation of Stadia Games and Entertainment, with [[Jade Raymond]] as its lead. Besides developing their own games, Stadia Games and Entertainment will help support the transition of third-party titles to the Stadia service.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.pcgamer.com/jade-raymond-is-heading-googles-first-party-game-studio/ | title = Jade Raymond is heading Google's first-party game studio |first = Andy | last = Chalk | date = March 19, 2019 | accessdate = March 19, 2019 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref>\n\n===Stadia Games and Entertainment===\nAlongside Stadia, Google established the Stadia Games and Entertainment division in Montreal around March 2019, with industry veteran [[Jade Raymond]] as its head. This division will focus on internal development of games for Stadia in addition to those they have obtained from third parties.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/19/18272996/google-stadia-studio-games-entertainment-exclusives-gdc-2019 | title=  Google created its own studio for Stadia-exclusive games | first = Andrew | last = Webster | date = March 19, 2019 | accessdate = December 30, 2019 | work = [[The Verge]] }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, the Stadia Games and Entertainment division acquired [[Typhoon Studios]] to develop additional content for the platform.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-12-19-stadia-acquires-typhoon-studios | title = Stadia acquires Typhoon Studios | first = Brendan | last = Sinclair | date = December 19, 2019 | accessdate = December 19, 2019 | work = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] }}</ref>\n\nA second Stadia studio, located in [[Playa Vista, Los Angeles]], was opened in March 2020, led by former [[SIE Santa Monica Studio|Sony Santa Monica]] head Shannon Studstill.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/359083/Google_picks_California_as_the_home_for_its_second_Stadia_studio.php | title = Google picks California as the home for its second Stadia studio | first = Alex | last = Wawro | date = March 4, 2020 | accessdate = March 4, 2020 | work = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref>\n\n== Availability ==\nStadia launched in November 2019 in fourteen countries: Belgium, Canada, Denmark, Finland, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Netherlands, Norway, Spain, Sweden, the United Kingdom, and the United States, and at that time, limited to the Pro tier users. By 2020, Google plans to expand Stadia to more countries.\n\nIn April 2020 Google made Stadia available to anyone in the initially supported countries. <ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.blog.google/products/stadia/try-stadia-free-today/ | title = Play Stadia Pro for free, starting today | first = Phil | last = Harrison | date = April 8, 2020 | accessdate = April 8, 2020 | work = [[Google Stadia]] }}</ref> \n\n== Games ==\nStadia requires users to purchase games to use over the service, though it offers a library of free games over time for Pro tier subscribers, as well as the first two years of ''[[Destiny 2]]'' content for free for those who purchased the Founder's Pack.<ref name=\"verge\">{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/6/18654632/google-stadia-price-release-date-games-bethesda-ea-doom-ubisoft-e3-2019 | title = Google\u2019s Stadia game service is officially coming November: Everything you need to know | first =Sean | last= Hollister | date = June 6, 2019 | access-date = June 6, 2019 | work = [[The Verge]] }}</ref> At the time of the platform's full reveal in June 2019, Google announced that ''Gylt'' by [[Tequila Works]] and ''Get Packed'' by Moonshine Studios would be exclusive to Stadia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/6/18655380/google-stadia-games-list-cloud-streaming-service-e3-2019|title=Here are all the games coming to Google\u2019s Stadia cloud streaming service|last=Warren|first=Tom|date=2019-06-06|website=The Verge|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref> The service launched with 22 games, and added 4 more in December 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://gematsu.com/2019/11/stadia-launch-lineup-announced | title = Stadia launch lineup announced | first = Sal | last = Romano | date = November 11, 2019 | accessdate = November 11, 2019 | work = [[Gematsu]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamer.com/the-google-stadia-launch-line-up-has-nearly-doubled/ | title = The Google Stadia launch line-up has nearly doubled | first= Shaun | last = Prescott | date = November 16, 2019 | accessdate = November 16, 2019 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Google announced that it planned to release over 120 games for Stadia during that year, of which 10 were timed-[[Platform exclusivity|exclusives]] set to release in the first half of the year.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-01-16-google-promises-more-than-10-stadia-timed-exclusives-by-july-2020 | title = Google promises more than 10 Stadia timed-exclusives by July 2020 | first = Wesley | last = Yin-Poole | date = January 16, 2020 | accessdate = January 16, 2020 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" width=\"auto\" id=\"softwarelist\"\n|+ List of games on Stadia\n! Title\n! Genre(s)\n! Developer(s)\n! Publisher(s)\n! Stadia release date\n! Original release date{{efn|Date of first completed public release, regardless of platform or region.}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Assassin's Creed Odyssey]]''\n| [[Action role-playing]]\n| [[Ubisoft Quebec]]\n| [[Ubisoft]]\n| {{dts|November 19, 2019|format=mdy}}\n| {{dts|October 5, 2018|format=mdy}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Attack on Titan 2]]: Final Battle''\n| [[Hack and slash]]\n| [[Omega Force]]\n| [[Koei Tecmo]]\n| {{dts|November 19, 2019|format=mdy}}\n| {{dts|2018-03-15|format=mdy}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Avengers (2020 video game)|Marvel's Avengers]]''\n| [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]]\n| [[Crystal Dynamics]]\n| [[Square Enix]]\n| {{TBA}}\n| {{dts|2020-09-04|format=mdy}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Baldur's Gate III]]''\n| [[Action role-playing]]\n| [[Larian Studios]]\n| [[Wizards of the Coast]]\n| {{TBA}}\n| {{TBA}}<!--{{dts|XXXX-XX-XX|format=mdy}}-->\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Borderlands 3]]''\n| [[First-person shooter]]\n| [[Gearbox Software]]\n| [[2K Games]]\n| {{dts|December 17, 2019|format=mdy}}\n| {{dts|September 13, 2019|format=mdy}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Crew 2]]''\n| [[Racing video game|Racing]]\n| [[Ivory Tower (company)|Ivory Tower]]\n| [[Ubisoft]]\n| {{dts|March 25, 2020|format=mdy}}\n| {{dts|June 29, 2018|format=mdy}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Cris Tales''\n| [[Role-playing video game|Role-playing]]\n| Dreams Uncorporated, SYCK\n| Modus Games\n| {{dts|2020|format=y}}\n| {{dts|2020|format=y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Cyberpunk 2077]]''\n| [[Role-playing video game|Role-playing]]\n| [[CD Projekt Red]]\n| [[CD Projekt]]\n| {{TBA}}\n| {{dts|September 17, 2020|format=mdy}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Darksiders Genesis]]''\n| [[Action role-playing]]\n| Airship Syndicate\n| [[THQ Nordic]]\n| {{dts|December 5, 2019|format=mdy}}\n| {{dts|December 5, 2019|format=mdy}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | '